replyContent: Hi Dennis, We‚Äôre confident in the randomization algorithm we use. It shuffles the deck at random, and with 52 cards there are roughly 80,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000 ways to arrange a single deck. Any similarities are most likely just a coincidence!

I'm afraid the other reviewer is right. This is supposed to give you a random hand to play, which means that you should win - assuming you know the basic strategy - at least one in every 20 or so plays. That is not the case here.  I am sure this is not on purpose as if I were writing a game and wanted to "rig" it I would likely default it the other way. But something in this is creating decks with abnormally high concentrations of red or black that make it nearly impossible to win if you use Draw 3. If you do a one card you will win a little over 50% of the time, but on one card it should be more than that.  You can check the main wikipedia article on Klondike for a discussion of the odds. This program is not working right, and hopefully the developers will look into why.
